{
    "metadata": {
        "description": "Enterprise IT helpdesk automation pipeline that receives raw support emails, redacts PII, classifies incidents by category and priority, and produces structured ServiceNow-ready incident payloads."
        "tags": ["itsm", "servicenow", "pii", "enterprise", "it-helpdesk"]
        "sample_queries": [
            "From: alice.wong@acmecorp.com\nOur prod Postgres cluster started throwing connection timeouts. Call +1-800-555-0199. Password was dbPass123.",
            "I can't connect to the VPN since this morning. Getting error DNS_PROBE_FINISHED.",
            "My Active Directory account got locked after too many failed login attempts."
        ]
    },

    include "config/llm_config.hocon",

    "tools": [

        # Front agent — entry point for all incoming IT support requests.
        # This is the "Front Man" and must be the first tool in the array.
        {
            "name": "it_service_desk",
            "function": {
                "description": """Enterprise IT helpdesk orchestrator. Receives a raw IT support
request (email, chat message, or incident report), routes it through a
PII scrubbing stage, classifies the incident, and returns a structured
ServiceNow incident payload."""
            },
            "instructions": """You are an enterprise IT helpdesk pipeline orchestrator.

When you receive a user request you MUST execute this exact pipeline in order:

Step 1 - Call pii_scrubber with the raw user request text.
Step 2 - Pass the clean_text output from Step 1 to ticket_classifier.
Step 3 - Pass the category, priority, and clean_text to ticket_builder.
Step 4 - Return the final ServiceNow payload from ticket_builder to the user.

Rules:
- Never skip or reorder steps.
- Never classify the ticket yourself without calling ticket_classifier.
- Never expose PII. Always pass through pii_scrubber first.
- Return the ticket_builder output exactly as-is.""",
            "tools": [
                "pii_scrubber",
                "ticket_classifier",
                "ticket_builder"
            ]
        },

        # PII scrubber — coded tool (no LLM, pure regex, deterministic)
        {
            "name": "pii_scrubber",
            "function": {
                "description": """Coded tool. Removes PII and credentials from raw IT support text
using 5-pass regex redaction before the text reaches any LLM. Handles
phone numbers, email addresses, structured credentials, prose credentials,
and email header lines.""",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "raw_text": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Raw IT support text that may contain PII or credentials"
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["raw_text"]
                }
            },
            "class": "pii_scrubber.PiiScrubberTool"
        },

        # Ticket classifier — LLM agent with strict output vocabulary
        {
            "name": "ticket_classifier",
            "function": {
                "description": """Classifies a PII-scrubbed IT support request into a structured
incident definition with category (Network, Database, Hardware, IAM)
and priority (HIGH, MEDIUM, LOW).""",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "clean_text": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "PII-scrubbed IT support text ready for classification"
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["clean_text"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """You are a strict enterprise IT incident classifier.

Analyze the provided clean_text and output ONLY a valid JSON object with
exactly these three keys:

{
  "category": "<exactly one of: Network, Database, Hardware, IAM>",
  "priority": "<exactly one of: HIGH, MEDIUM, LOW>",
  "justification": "<single sentence, max 200 characters>"
}

Category rules:
- Network:  connectivity loss, VPN failure, DNS errors, firewall blocks, latency
- Database: DB timeouts, query failures, replication lag, cluster unreachable
- Hardware: disk failures, memory errors, physical server down, device fault
- IAM:      login denied, access revoked, password reset needed, permission gap

Priority rules:
- HIGH:   production system down, data loss risk, 50+ users affected, security breach
- MEDIUM: degraded performance, workaround available, 10-50 users affected
- LOW:    single user affected, cosmetic issue, non-urgent enhancement

Output ONLY the JSON object. No markdown fences. No explanatory text. No extra keys."""
        },

        # Ticket builder — coded tool (no LLM, builds final ServiceNow JSON)
        {
            "name": "ticket_builder",
            "function": {
                "description": """Coded tool. Builds a complete ServiceNow Incident Table JSON
payload from the classifier output. Maps priority labels (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW)
to ServiceNow urgency/impact/priority fields (1/2/3).""",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "clean_text": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "PII-scrubbed incident description text"
                        },
                        "category": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Incident category: Network, Database, Hardware, or IAM"
                        },
                        "priority": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Incident priority: HIGH, MEDIUM, or LOW"
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["clean_text", "category", "priority"]
                }
            },
            "class": "ticket_builder.TicketBuilderTool"
        }
    ]
}
